<Base
  title="02 · Framework, Theory & Principles — Interphase"
  current="02 · Framework"
  prev={{ href: `${base}/01-concept`, num: '01', title: 'Strategic Foundation' }}
  next={{ href: `${base}/03-product`, num: '03', title: 'Tech Stack & MVP' }}
>
  <!-- COVER -->
  <section class="cover">
    <div class="shell">
      <p class="eyebrow cover-eyebrow">02 · Foundational Documents · 2026</p>
      <h1>Framework,<br /><em>theory</em> &amp;<br />principles.</h1>
      <p class="cover-sub">
        Conceptual framework (including values), theory of change, and the full
        set of design principles that govern architecture, product, and market
        positioning.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================================================
       A. CONCEPTUAL FRAMEWORK
       ============================================================ -->

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">§A · Conceptual framework</p>
        <h2>Conditions for healthy<br /><em>transformation.</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p class="lead">Interphase is founded on a single conviction: organisations fail at change not because people are resistant, but because the conditions for healthy transformation are never installed. The platform installs those conditions — continuously, at scale, and at the level of the individual.</p>

          <h3>A.1 — The core metaphor</h3>

          <p>The name and the logic derive from cell biology. Before a cell can divide, it must complete Interphase: a period of growth, metabolic activity, DNA replication, and error-checking. Skip this phase, and division produces damaged, fragile, or malignant cells. Organisations skip their equivalent phase every time they announce a restructuring, complete an M&amp;A, or mandate an ESG rollout — without corresponding internal preparation.</p>

          <div class="pull">
            <blockquote>"The organisation is a living organism. Change is cell division. Interphase is the missing phase that makes division healthy rather than destructive."</blockquote>
            <div class="attr">Core metaphor — Interphase</div>
          </div>

          <p>This metaphor is not decorative. It is structurally generative: it names the platform, defines its four-layer architecture, explains the failure modes it addresses, and provides an intuitive language for explaining the product. The biological framing carries an implicit claim: the current approach to change management is, biologically speaking, abnormal — a pathology, not a strategy.</p>

          <p>The metaphor further distinguishes Interphase from tools that treat change as a workflow, a communication problem, or a training gap. Change is metabolic. It requires energy, time, and internal processing — not a series of managed events. Interphase provides the environment in which that processing can happen.</p>

          <h3>A.2 — The four layers</h3>

          <p>The conceptual architecture maps each biological cell structure to a functional platform layer. These are not product features — they are the structural logic of how change is metabolised at different scales, from the individual to the collective.</p>

          <div class="rows">
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">L4</div>
              <div class="row-label">Outermost<strong>Organism</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>Collective evolution</h4>
                <p>The organisation as a whole becomes self-aware of how it changes. Patterns across teams, transformation cycles, and time horizons are visible at the leadership level as aggregate insight — not surveillance. The organism develops an immune memory: it knows how it has processed change before and can prepare more efficiently for what comes next. This is the emergent, self-sustaining outcome of the other three layers operating well.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">L3</div>
              <div class="row-label">Data layer<strong>Metabolic</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>Real-time capacity building</h4>
                <p>Anonymised reflection data from the Nucleus, read and interpreted by Chaperones in real time, drives the deployment of targeted learning modules at the moment they are most needed. If the aggregate data shows a cohort cycling through anxiety about role ambiguity, the metabolic layer surfaces a trust-building module — not as a generic HR programme, but as a precise intervention. This is the intelligence engine of the platform.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">L2</div>
              <div class="row-label">Human layer<strong>Cytoplasm</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>Human-guided capacity building</h4>
                <p>Certified practitioners — coaches, OD consultants, change managers — use the anonymised data stream from the Nucleus to guide structured capacity-building sessions. They do not read individual reflections. They read the texture of collective processing: where energy is accumulating, where it is stuck. Their interventions are timed by data and executed with human judgment.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">L1</div>
              <div class="row-label">Foundation<strong>Nucleus</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>Individual reflection &amp; transparency</h4>
                <p>Each employee has a private, AI-assisted reflection space where they can process the organisational changes they are living through. The AI generates questions — never answers — calibrated to the individual's current reflective capacity. The interface is ambient and contextual: it arrives at the right moment, asks a few good questions, and disappears. This layer produces the raw material for everything above it.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>The layers are designed to function in sequence and in parallel. The Nucleus produces data that feeds the Metabolic. The Metabolic informs Chaperone intervention in the Cytoplasm. The Cytoplasm's outputs accumulate into Organism-level intelligence. And the Organism layer, when functioning, feeds back into how the Nucleus calibrates its questions — creating a genuinely adaptive system.</p>

          <h3>A.3 — Values</h3>

          <p>These are not aspirational statements. They are functional commitments — decisions about what the platform will and will not do, which can be tested against every product, architecture, and market decision.</p>

          <div class="two-col">
            <div class="tc-cell">
              <h4>Agency · over direction</h4>
              <p>The platform never tells people what to think, feel, or do. It creates the conditions in which they can discover what they already know. Every design choice is tested against this: does it expand or constrain the individual's sense of agency?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tc-cell">
              <h4>Safety · over efficiency</h4>
              <p>Honest reflection only happens in genuinely safe conditions. Privacy is not a legal requirement — it is the platform's primary operating condition. When in doubt between a more efficient feature and a safer one, safety wins.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tc-cell">
              <h4>Depth · over speed</h4>
              <p>Change that is processed superficially tends to recur. Interphase is built around the conviction that genuine metabolisation of change takes time, and that creating the conditions for depth is more valuable than accelerating throughput.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tc-cell">
              <h4>Continuity · over events</h4>
              <p>A single workshop changes nothing. An ambient, persistent infrastructure changes everything — slowly, invisibly, and durably. The platform is not a programme that an organisation runs. It is a layer that an organisation inhabits.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tc-cell">
              <h4>Humanity · over automation</h4>
              <p>AI handles the questions; humans handle the meaning. The Chaperone model is not a concession to technology limitations — it is a philosophical position. Some things should be done by people because the human presence is itself part of what makes it work.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tc-cell">
              <h4>Emergence · over prescription</h4>
              <p>The platform does not define what a "good" transformation outcome looks like. It creates the conditions for each organisation's own intelligence to surface. The Organism layer is not built — it emerges from the other three operating well.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================================================
       B. THEORY OF CHANGE
       ============================================================ -->

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">§B · Theory of change</p>
        <h2>If we do this,<br /><em>under what conditions,</em><br />does that result?</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p class="lead">A theory of change answers a precise question: if we do X, under what conditions, through what mechanisms, will Y result? For Interphase, X is ambient, AI-assisted, human-guided reflection infrastructure. Y is organisations that are durably capable of absorbing change without cellular failure.</p>

          <h3>B.1 — Preconditions for change</h3>

          <p>The theory only holds if the following conditions are met. These are not assumptions about the market — they are design requirements. If any precondition fails, the change logic breaks.</p>

          <div class="rows">
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">01</div>
              <div class="row-label">Trust<strong>Psychological safety</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>Employees must genuinely believe their reflections are private and cannot be traced back to them. If this is in doubt, reflections become performances — and the data layer becomes noise.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">02</div>
              <div class="row-label">UX<strong>Low-friction</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>If documentation feels like a tax, people stop. The reflection experience must feel conversational, not administrative. This is a UX precondition, not a user education problem.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">03</div>
              <div class="row-label">Practitioners<strong>Genuine expertise</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>The human layer is only as good as the practitioners in it. Certification must be rigorous, not a rubber stamp. A poor Chaperone undermines the entire model.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">04</div>
              <div class="row-label">Leadership<strong>Aggregate response</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>The anonymised dashboard is only valuable if leadership can sit with aggregate discomfort and respond systemically, not reactively or punitively. Willingness to see without acting on individuals is non-negotiable.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">05</div>
              <div class="row-label">Context<strong>Real transformation</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>Interphase is not a wellness tool or an engagement platform. It functions best when there is real friction to process. The change context is the feedstock.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">06</div>
              <div class="row-label">Patience<strong>Time for metabolism</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>Interphase is not a quick fix. If an organisation expects results in six weeks, the theory fails. The platform requires a commitment to continuity — typically a minimum of one full transformation cycle to show measurable outcomes.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3>B.2 — The change logic</h3>

          <p>Given the preconditions above, the following is the causal chain through which Interphase produces its outcomes. Each step includes the key assumption on which it depends.</p>

          <div class="rows">
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">1</div>
              <div class="row-label">Input<strong>Real change</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>Employees experience organisational change</h4>
                <p>A transformation trigger is active — M&amp;A, ESG mandate, leadership succession, digital rollout, or structural reorganisation. The change is real, and employees are living through it. This is the raw material: unprocessed experience of friction, uncertainty, opportunity, and loss.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:14px; font-size:13.5px; color:var(--ink-mute); font-style:italic;"><strong>Assumption</strong> — the change is significant enough that employees have a genuine need to process it, not merely a routine policy update.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">2</div>
              <div class="row-label">Mechanism · Nucleus<strong>Conditions for reflection</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>The platform creates conditions for reflection</h4>
                <p>The interface arrives at contextually appropriate moments — after significant meetings, during calendar gaps, at the close of a transformation phase. It asks a small number of precise, open questions calibrated to the individual's reflective capacity. The interaction is brief, multimodal, and low-friction. Crucially, it asks for observation before interpretation: "what did you notice?" before "what do you think it means?"</p>
                <p style="margin-top:14px; font-size:13.5px; color:var(--ink-mute); font-style:italic;"><strong>Assumption</strong> — the interface is ambient and low-friction enough that employees engage voluntarily and honestly, rather than treating it as another HR compliance task.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">3</div>
              <div class="row-label">Mechanism · Individual<strong>Capacity built</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>Reflection builds individual capacity</h4>
                <p>Over repeated interactions, the individual's ability to reflect increases — more dimensions engaged, more differentiation within each dimension. They become better at noticing what is happening to them, and better at separating their own experience from the organisation's narrative about that experience. This is not personal development as a side-effect — it is the primary mechanism of change readiness.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:14px; font-size:13.5px; color:var(--ink-mute); font-style:italic;"><strong>Assumption</strong> — reflective capacity is developable through repeated practice at the right level of challenge. The AI can detect and calibrate to current capacity reliably.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">4</div>
              <div class="row-label">Mechanism · Metabolic<strong>Patterns visible</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>Anonymised data reveals collective patterns</h4>
                <p>Individual reflections, stripped of any identifying information, aggregate into a real-time picture of how the organisation as a whole is processing the change. Where is energy accumulating? Where is it stuck? Which teams are cycling through the same anxiety? This data is not a survey result — it is a living texture of organisational experience, updated continuously, and readable by Chaperones.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:14px; font-size:13.5px; color:var(--ink-mute); font-style:italic;"><strong>Assumption</strong> — the anonymisation architecture is robust enough that employees genuinely trust it, and that trust translates into honest rather than managed reflections.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">5</div>
              <div class="row-label">Mechanism · Cytoplasm<strong>Targeted intervention</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>Chaperones deploy targeted capacity-building</h4>
                <p>Certified Chaperones read the aggregate data and use it to time and design capacity-building sessions for the teams or cohorts that need them most. They are not generic trainers delivering a fixed programme — they are practitioners using live organisational intelligence to intervene at the moment of maximum leverage. Their sessions are not about the change itself; they are about the capacity to process change.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:14px; font-size:13.5px; color:var(--ink-mute); font-style:italic;"><strong>Assumption</strong> — Chaperones can correctly interpret aggregate data signals and translate them into effective interventions. This requires both data literacy and genuine facilitation expertise.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">6</div>
              <div class="row-label">Mechanism · Flywheel<strong>Self-reinforcing</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>Each cycle deepens the capacity</h4>
                <p>The more someone uses Interphase, the better they become at reflection, the more honest their contributions to the data layer, the more precisely Chaperones can intervene, and the more effective those interventions are. This is the motivation flywheel: individual competence drives collective intelligence, which drives better support, which drives more engagement.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:14px; font-size:13.5px; color:var(--ink-mute); font-style:italic;"><strong>Assumption</strong> — intrinsic motivation to reflect increases as reflective competence increases. The platform must not rely on extrinsic motivation (gamification, reminders, manager pressure).</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">7</div>
              <div class="row-label">Outcome · Organism<strong>Fluency built</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>The organisation develops transformation fluency</h4>
                <p>After one or more full transformation cycles on the platform, the organisation has developed something that did not exist before: genuine cultural capacity to absorb change. Not a plan for the next transformation — a metabolic capability that applies to any transformation. Leaders understand how their culture processes change. Employees have stronger reflective capacity and greater psychological safety. The organisation has an immune memory of its own change patterns.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:14px; font-size:13.5px; color:var(--ink-mute); font-style:italic;"><strong>Assumption</strong> — transformation fluency is transferable across different change contexts. Capacity built during an M&amp;A integration will meaningfully accelerate readiness for a subsequent digital rollout.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3>B.3 — Intended outcomes</h3>

          <p>Outcomes are expressed at three levels: individual, team, and organisational. Each level has both a primary outcome and a commercially measurable indicator — because the theory of change must be testable.</p>

          <div class="tiles">
            <div class="tile">
              <h4>Individual</h4>
              <div class="big">Reflective capacity</div>
              <p>Each person who uses Interphase over a full transformation cycle develops a stronger ability to process change — to hold more dimensions simultaneously, to differentiate within them more finely, and to connect their own experience to the organisational picture without losing themselves in it.</p>
              <p style="margin-top:14px; font-size:11px; font-family:var(--mono); color:var(--ink); letter-spacing:0.06em;">Indicator → Reduced burnout signals; higher engagement during transformation phases</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tile">
              <h4>Team</h4>
              <div class="big">Collective intelligence</div>
              <p>Teams that use Interphase together develop a shared language for processing change — and a greater tolerance for ambiguity. The Chaperone layer builds trust and relational safety within the team that extends beyond the transformation context.</p>
              <p style="margin-top:14px; font-size:11px; font-family:var(--mono); color:var(--ink); letter-spacing:0.06em;">Indicator → Faster conflict resolution; lower churn during transformation periods</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tile">
              <h4>Organisation</h4>
              <div class="big">Transformation fluency</div>
              <p>The organisation builds an immune memory of how it changes. Leadership can see, in aggregate, how change is being metabolised — and can intervene earlier, more precisely, and with greater confidence in the outcome. The 70% failure rate is the baseline this is measured against.</p>
              <p style="margin-top:14px; font-size:11px; font-family:var(--mono); color:var(--ink); letter-spacing:0.06em;">Indicator → Transformation completion rates; ROI on change investments</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================================================
       C. DESIGN PRINCIPLES
       ============================================================ -->

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">§C · Design principles</p>
        <h2>Convictions, <em>not rules.</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p class="lead">Design principles are not implementation rules. They are convictions about what is true — about people, about systems, about the relationship between the two. Everything built, sold, or decided within Interphase should be traceable back to one of these principles. If it cannot be traced, it does not belong.</p>

          <h3>C.1 — Architecture principles</h3>

          <div class="rows">
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">A1</div>
              <div class="row-label">Architecture<strong>Continuous over event-based</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>The platform is persistent infrastructure — not a project with a start and end date. It installs a continuous, ambient layer of organisational self-awareness that operates across transformation cycles, not within a single one. Architecturally expressed as an always-on platform, not a deployable module.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:var(--ink-mute);">→ <em>Implication.</em> SaaS subscription model; no project-based pricing.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">A2</div>
              <div class="row-label">Architecture<strong>One engine, many lenses</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>The core reflection engine — AI questions, data aggregation, Chaperone protocol — is built once and reconfigured through interpretive lenses for different deployment contexts: corporate transformation, OSCC governance, Soul.com consumer. The front-end UX rarely changes. What changes is the interpretive framework. Modularity must be baked in from V1 — not retrofitted.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:var(--ink-mute);">→ <em>Implication.</em> Lens licensing as B2B2B revenue stream; multi-market leverage from a single core build.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">A3</div>
              <div class="row-label">Architecture<strong>Anonymisation is structural</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>Individual reflections cannot be traced to specific people — not by policy, but by architecture. The system aggregates at a level that makes individual attribution technically impossible, not merely contractually prohibited. Honest data only flows in conditions of genuine, demonstrable safety.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:var(--ink-mute);">→ <em>Implication.</em> Minimum aggregation thresholds built into the data model; no individual-level exports available to any user.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">A4</div>
              <div class="row-label">Architecture<strong>Data moat by design</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>The platform's primary defensibility is the accumulation of richly contextualised organisational data over multiple transformation cycles. A competitor can copy the UI; they cannot copy five years of an organisation's change patterns, language, and learning texture. The data layer is designed to be maximally contextualised — tagged to transformation type, organisational layer, and time — from day one.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:var(--ink-mute);">→ <em>Implication.</em> Data schema designed for longitudinal analysis from V1; switching costs as depth accumulates.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">A5</div>
              <div class="row-label">Architecture<strong>Four layers, stackable</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>The four biological layers are architecturally distinct and incrementally deployable. A client can start with the Nucleus only — individual reflection + basic dashboard — and layer in Chaperone engagement and module marketplace access as their relationship with the platform matures. This is also the MVP logic.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:var(--ink-mute);">→ <em>Implication.</em> MVP is Nucleus only; other layers are post-validation additions.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3>C.2 — Product principles</h3>

          <div class="rows">
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">P1</div>
              <div class="row-label">Product<strong>Documentation as by-product</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>Reflection must feel so low-friction that documentation becomes a natural consequence of conversation, not an extra task. The interface comes to you at the right moment, asks one or two good questions, and disappears. The person never performs an administrative act. The record is produced by the conversation, not alongside it.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:var(--ink-mute);">→ <em>Implication.</em> No explicit "save" or "submit" actions; session closes automatically; no minimum word counts.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">P2</div>
              <div class="row-label">Product<strong>Questions, never answers</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>The AI does not give feedback, validate, diagnose, or confirm. It asks questions only — always grounded in direct experience, always asking for specifics before generalisations, always orienting the person toward their own insight. The value is the conditions Interphase creates for the person to discover what they already know.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:var(--ink-mute);">→ <em>Implication.</em> No sentiment scoring shown to users; no "your top themes this week" outputs; no behavioural recommendations.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">P3</div>
              <div class="row-label">Product<strong>Emotional neutrality</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>The interface never validates, encourages, or rewards. No "great insight!" No streaks. No completion badges. Once people sense they are being evaluated — even positively — they optimise for the evaluation rather than for honesty.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:var(--ink-mute);">→ <em>Implication.</em> No gamification layer; no notification design that creates urgency or reward; tone calibrated to warm-neutral throughout.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">P4</div>
              <div class="row-label">Product<strong>Calibrated complexity</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>The AI tracks two axes of reflective maturity — dimensioning (how many layers of reality the person engages simultaneously) and differentiation (how many angles within any dimension). Questions are calibrated to current capacity: always stretching slightly, never overwhelming, never boring.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:var(--ink-mute);">→ <em>Implication.</em> AI must maintain a model of each user's current reflective capacity and update it per session.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">P5</div>
              <div class="row-label">Product<strong>Contextual triggering</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>Interphase integrates with calendar and email workflows — not to surveil, but to sense the rhythm of working life. It knows when a significant meeting has just ended and a 15-minute window exists before the next one. The timing is the UX. A question asked at the wrong moment is noise; the same question asked immediately after the experience is an insight.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:var(--ink-mute);">→ <em>Implication.</em> Calendar API integration is a V1 requirement; triggering logic must be configurable by the user.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">P6</div>
              <div class="row-label">Product<strong>The motivation flywheel</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>Low-effort experience → growing competence → autonomy &amp; relational safety → intrinsic motivation to return → richer reflections → deeper learning → stronger bond with the interface. The system must generate its own gravity. If engagement requires external enforcement, the product has failed.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:var(--ink-mute);">→ <em>Implication.</em> Success metric is voluntary return rate, not prompted engagement rate.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">P7</div>
              <div class="row-label">Product<strong>Multimodal &amp; local-first</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>Input is voice, text, photo, or short video — whatever form the thought wants to take. Content is captured on-device and synced when connectivity allows. No reflection is ever lost to a poor connection. The user's job is to express, not to organise.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:var(--ink-mute);">→ <em>Implication.</em> Offline-first architecture for mobile; voice transcription as default input mode.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3>C.3 — Market principles</h3>

          <div class="rows">
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">M1</div>
              <div class="row-label">Market<strong>Infrastructure, not tooling</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>Interphase occupies the infrastructure layer — beneath IT-change tooling, beneath HR engagement platforms, beneath consulting engagements. It does not compete with these categories; it becomes the substrate they require. Interphase is not a better Culture Amp. It is the layer that makes Culture Amp's data more meaningful.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:var(--ink-mute);">→ <em>Implication.</em> Positioning sentence always references "infrastructure" and "Cultural Architecture" — never "platform" or "tool" in isolation.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">M2</div>
              <div class="row-label">Market<strong>Chaperones as channel</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>Certified external practitioners bring their existing client bases to the platform and serve as the primary delivery channel for the human layer. Each Chaperone is simultaneously a delivery partner, a go-to-market channel, and a quality signal. This scales professional services without Interphase bearing headcount cost.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:var(--ink-mute);">→ <em>Implication.</em> Chaperone certification programme is a V1 requirement; revenue share model must be economically compelling.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">M3</div>
              <div class="row-label">Market<strong>Beachhead discipline</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>The natural first client is a mid-market European enterprise (250–5,000 employees) undergoing a defined transformation trigger. Anything outside this definition is a distraction until the beachhead is established. Beachhead discipline is not modest ambition; it is the fastest path to Series A credibility.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:var(--ink-mute);">→ <em>Implication.</em> First three paying clients must match the beachhead definition exactly; no exceptions for interesting logos.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">M4</div>
              <div class="row-label">Market<strong>Measurable ROI at every layer</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>Every outcome the platform claims must be commercially measurable — against a baseline that exists before deployment. "We made the culture better" is not a result. "Voluntary churn during the M&amp;A integration was 40% lower than your last comparable integration" is a result. The measurement framework is designed before deployment, not after.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:var(--ink-mute);">→ <em>Implication.</em> Pre-deployment diagnostic is a standard onboarding component; outcome measurement is contractually agreed at the start.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">M5</div>
              <div class="row-label">Market<strong>Philosophy as moat</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>The biological framing, the Chaperone model, the no-answers AI philosophy, and the multi-lens architecture cannot be copy-pasted. They require a distinctive philosophical foundation that takes years to build credibly. The moat is not technical — it is conceptual.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:var(--ink-mute);">→ <em>Implication.</em> Founder-led thought leadership is a strategic asset; the biological metaphor must be embedded in every client touchpoint.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">M6</div>
              <div class="row-label">Market<strong>Three-layer revenue coherence</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>The SaaS platform, Chaperone network, and module marketplace must be designed so that each layer reinforces the others — not so that clients can bypass the human layer, or Chaperones can operate without the platform. The revenue architecture is an expression of the conceptual framework.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:var(--ink-mute);">→ <em>Implication.</em> Module marketplace available to Chaperones only, not directly to organisations; SaaS pricing includes Chaperone access as default.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
